,Recommended,252150,20600613,"Posted: 17 January, 2016",all,R34LM,"I found this game to be very enjoyable.The basic premise is that you play as a disgutsing littly dude named Grimm who wishes to take away all the neat and tidy and childish out of commonly known fairy tales and replace them with filth, gore and dark undertones.The game itself was released in an episodic fashion when it was brand new, coming out every week, but now all three seasons are here.Each episode and gameplay plays out the same. You begin with Grimm telling you the cutesy version of the fairy tale in the episode (ranging from Father Death, Frog Prince and Snow White as a series finale). When that story is finished, you enter each scene as Grimm and begin spreading filth. Grimm has an aura/radius of darkness that turns the light hearted terrain and objects into darkness. Starting off, you can only convert buckets and flowers, but as you convert more you gain more points towards your darkness level (shown at the top of the screen). Higher levels of darkness means a wider aura, faster speed, higher jumping, and, most importantly, the ability to convert larger objects. During the conversion, fairy tale characters and creatures will attempt to clean up the mess, but they don't prove to be much of an issue.The usual goal in each scene is getting to a certain level of darkness and then ""butt-stomping' (jump twice) the plot point to proceed. Once all scenes have been converted, the story is then retold in its raw and dark way and the episode is over.The art style fits the theme of the game, with really childish creatures that turn into ugly monstrosities. It's just enjoyable to see what one fairy tale object will convert to, such as a regular tree turning into a tree filled with hanging corpses.The humor within this game ranges from fart jokes to satire to black humor, all of which makes the game much mor enjoyable. Grimm himself is an enjoyable narrator and character. Fun fact: the voice actor for Grimm voices EVERY character in the game, which shows off the guy's incredible voice talent.The one downside is that once you play one episode you basically have played them all. The gameplay is the same through each episode, though some introduce other gameplay elements.To defend that point, however, the game is built around the narration of the story and the curiosity of how each story (and every object in it) will look after Grimm has converted it. So, even though the gameplay is the same, it is a different story to muck up. The choices in fairy tales are great, too.If you don't mind the repetitive gameplay, definitely give this game a go. Sometimes it is good to pass 30 minutes of time by playing an episode, and you got three series of episodes to play, which will keep you occupied."
